According to shrine tradition, '''when Yamato Takeru was on his eastern expedition, he encountered a great storm at sea'''. His wife, '''Ototachibana-hime''', sacrificed herself by leaping into the waters to calm the storm. Eventually, '''her garments and headgear drifted ashore at this location''', leading to the shrine’s foundation.

This legend aligns with the '''record in the Kojiki''', which states:

> *"After seven days, the Empress's comb washed up on the shore. The Emperor took the comb and built a tomb to enshrine it."*

Because of this connection, '''the Fujimidai Kofun (富士見台古墳), located on a nearby hill''', is sometimes considered to be '''Ototachibana-hime's burial site'''. However, no concrete historical evidence supports this claim<ref>[http://www.city.kawasaki.jp/880/page/0000000069.html Tachibana Shrine and Fujimidai Kofun (Kawasaki City Board of Education)]</ref>.

=== '''Fujimidai Kofun''' ===
Behind the shrine, atop a hill, lies the '''Fujimidai Kofun''', which some believe to be the resting place of '''Ototachibana-hime'''. However, '''archaeological findings suggest that the mound was built around the 6th century''', making it more likely the tomb of a '''local ruler of the time'''<ref>[http://homepage2.nifty.com/plaza-k/name/ntaka/mizo13.htm Plaza Takatsu - Place Name Exploration - Fujimidai]</ref>.

In '''modern times''', the area around '''Fujimidai''' has been heavily urbanized. The city of Kawasaki developed the site into a '''residential area''', renaming it '''"Shimoguchi Fujimidai"'''. The ancient burial mound, once a '''prominent hill overlooking the Tama River''', has been partially leveled for development. Today, '''only a portion remains''', measuring '''3.7 meters in height''' and '''17.5 meters in diameter''', and it is maintained as a '''public park'''.

== '''Deities Enshrined''' ==
* '''Main Deities:'''
  * [[Yamato Takeru]]
  * [[Ototachibana-hime]]

== '''Annual Events''' ==
* '''Main Festival:''' October 8

== '''Cultural Heritage''' ==
* '''Tachibana Shrine Main Hall (社殿)'''
  * The exact date of its original construction is unknown, but records confirm that it was '''rebuilt in 1851 (Kaei 4)'''.
  * In '''November 2018''', the shrine was designated a '''Kawasaki City Tangible Cultural Property'''<ref>[http://www.city.kawasaki.jp/880/page/0000101919.html Kawasaki City Board of Education - 1st Regional Cultural Property Designation]</ref><ref>[http://www.city.kawasaki.jp/880/page/0000120101.html Kawasaki City Board of Education - Regional Cultural Property Introduction]</ref>.

== '''Surrounding Area''' ==
Tachibana Shrine is located at the '''end of the "Tachibana Walking Path" (たちばなの散歩道)''', which extends from '''Kajigaya Station''' on the '''Tokyu Den-en-toshi Line'''. The area is rich in history, featuring:
* '''Shimoguchi Shell Mound (子母口貝塚)''' – A Jomon-period site
* '''Fujimidai Kofun (富士見台古墳)''' – Associated with Ototachibana-hime
* '''Yōgōji (影向寺)''' – A temple said to have been founded during the Hakuhō period
* '''Nōmanji (能満寺)''' – A former sub-temple (塔頭) of Yōgōji

Additionally, the shrine stands '''on the first plateau after crossing the Tama River via the Maruko Ferry (丸子の渡し)'''. This marks the entrance to the '''Tama Hills (多摩丘陵)'''.

== '''Access''' ==

=== '''By Train''' ===
* '''JR Nambu Line''':
  * '''Musashi-Shinjo Station''' – 20-minute walk or bus ride

=== '''By Bus''' ===
